especially the miracle stories, the figure of the Jew appears in an important role as Mary's enemy. Drawing from theological and legendary traditions dating back to early Christianity, monks revived the idea that Jews violently opposed the virgin mother of God; the goal of the monks was to contrast the veneration they thought Mary deserved with the resistance of the Jews. Kati Ihnat argues that the imagined antagonism of the Jews toward Mary came to serve an essential purpose in encouraging Christian devotion to her as merciful mother and heavenly Queen.Through an examination of miracles, sermons, liturgy, and theology, Mother of Mercy, Bane of the Jews reveals how English monks helped to establish an enduring rivalry between Mary and the Jews, in consolidating her as the most popular saint of the Middle Ages and in making devotion to her a foundational marker of Christian identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aJudaismvControversial literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAbraham.  aAnglo-Norman England.  aEadmer.  aImmaculate Conception.  aIncarnation.  aJews.  aLydda.  aMarian cult.  aMary.  aTheodore.  aTheophilus.  aToulouse.  abodily Assumption.  aconversion.  adevotion.  afeast.  ahagiographies.  aliturgy.  amass.  amiracle story.  amiracle.  amiracles.  amonks.  aoffice.  aprayer.  asalvation.  asermon.  atheology.  atreatises.  aveneration.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400883660zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400883660423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400883660.jpg  a978-3-11-063859-2  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aE